e web |title=Dafabet English Open (2017) |trans-title= |last=\u00c5rdalen |first=Hermund |work=snooker.org |access-date=30 December 2019 |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=627 |language=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024070600/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=627 |archive-date=24 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"snoo_Betw\">{{Cite web |title=Betway UK Championship (2017) |trans-title= |last=\u00c5rdalen |first=Hermund |work=snooker.org |access-date=30 December 2019 |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=624 |language=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212151243/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=624 |archive-date=12 December 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"snoo_ManB\">{{Cite web |title=ManBetX Welsh Open (2018)|trans-title= |last=\u00c5rdalen |first=Hermund |work=snooker.org |access-date=30 December 2019 |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=630 |language=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712034744/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=630 |archive-date=12 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Qualiresults\">{{cite web |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=604 |title=Betfred World Snooker Championship qualifiers 2018 results |work=snooker.org |accessdate=22 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910215547/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=604 |archive-date=10 September 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"worl_Main\">{{Cite web |title=Main Tour Qualification 2018/19 |work=World Snooker |access-date=30 December 2019 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/main-tour-qualification-2018-19/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609074218/http://www.worldsnooker.com/main-tour-qualification-2018-19/ |archive-date=9 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"indi_Pank\">{{Cite web |title=Pankaj Advani-Aditya Mehta pair wins World Team Snooker title |work=India Today |date=25 September 2019 |access-date=1 January 2020 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/other-sports/story/pankaj-advani-aditya-mehta-win-ibsf-world-team-snooker-title-1603130-2019-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101131109/https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/other-sports/story/pankaj-advani-aditya-mehta-win-ibsf-world-team-snooker-title-1603130-2019-09-25 |archive-date=1 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"hind_Pank\">{{Cite web |title=Pankaj Advani-Aditya Mehta pair wins World Team Snooker title |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=1 January 2020 |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/other-sports/pankaj-advani-aditya-mehta-pair-wins-world-team-snooker-title/story-Fl7VdzQK082K1KteEjfkSN.html |date=25 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227190715/https://www.hindustantimes.com/other-sports/pankaj-advani-aditya-mehta-pair-wins-world-team-snooker-title/story-Fl7VdzQK082K1KteEjfkSN.html |archive-date=27 December 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"rkgs_AVer\">{{Cite web |title=A Very Happy Birthday To The Sun Of Indian Snooker Player Aditya Mehta |work=rkgsnooker.com |access-date=2 April 2020 |url=https://www.rkgsnooker.com/articles/a-very-happy-birthday-to-the-sun-of-indian-snooker-player-aditya-mehta/token-72 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219064458/http://www.rkgsnooker.com/articles/a-very-happy-birthday-to-the-sun-of-indian-snooker-player-aditya-mehta/token-72 |archive-date=19 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"desi_5Top\">{{Cite web |title=5 Top Indian Snooker Players who have Shined in the Game |work=DESIblitz |access-date=2 April 2020 |url=https://www.desiblitz.com/content/5-top-indian-snooker-players-who-have-shined-in-the-game |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208125429/https://www.desiblitz.com/content/5-top-indian-snooker-players-who-have-shined-in-the-game |archive-date=8 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Y0WUS\">{{Cite web |title=ManBetX Gibraltar Open (2018)|trans-title= |last=\u00c5rdalen |first=Hermund |work=snooker.org |access-date=30 December 2019 |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=656 |language=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190519082102/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=656 |archive-date=19 May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"wtb3I\">{{Cite web |title=Story Of The 2018 Betfred World Championship |website=worldsnooker.com |publisher=World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association |date=8 May 2018 |access-date=5 December 2018 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/story-of-the-2018-betfred-world-championship/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509012935/http://www.worldsnooker.com/story-of-the-2018-betfred-world-championship/ |archive-date=9 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Aditya Mehta}}\n* \n*[http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/aditya-mehta/ Aditya Mehta] at ''worldsnooker.com''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090221035954/http://www.global-snooker.com/Aditya-Mehta.asp Profile on the Global Snooker]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mehta, Aditya}}\n[[Category:Indian snooker players]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cue sports players from Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:World Games gold medalists]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2013 World Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in cue sports]]\n[[Category:Asian Games silver medalists for India]]\n[[Category:Asian Games bronze medalists for India]]\n[[Category:Cue sports players at the 2006 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Cue sports players at the 2010 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2006 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2010 Asian Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Indian snooker player, born October 1985}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| name           = Aditya Mehta\n| image          = Aditya Mehta PHC 2017.jpg\n| caption        = Mehta at the [[2017 Paul Hunter Classic]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1985|10|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| Sport country  = {{IND}}\n| Nickname       = \"The Sun Of Indian Snooker\"\n| Professional   = 2008/2009, 2011\u20132018\n| High ranking   = 49 <small>(May\u2013June, August\u2013November 2014, February\u2013March 2015)</small>\n| Prize money  = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]157,333<ref name=\"snoo_Adit\" />\n| High break     = '''[[Maximum break|147]]''': <br> <small>[[2014 Paul Hunter Classic]]</small>\n| Century break = 41\n| Best finish    = Runner-up <small>([[2013 Indian Open]])</small>\n| Ranking wins   = \n| Other wins     = \n| World champ    = \n| medals        =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[snooker]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{IND}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[Cue sports at the 2013 World Games|2013 Cali]] | [[Snooker at the World Games 2013 \u2013 men's singles|Singles]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Games]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[Cue sports at the 2006 Asian Games|2006 Doha]] | [[Cue sports at the 2006 Asian Games \u2013 Men's snooker team|Team]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[Cue sports at the 2010 Asian Games|2010 Guangzhou]] | [[Cue sports at the 2010 Asian Games \u2013 Men's snooker singles|Singles]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[Cue sports at the 2010 Asian Games|2010 Guangzhou]] | [[Cue sports at the 2010 Asian Games \u2013 Men's snooker team|Team]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Indoor Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[Cue sports at the 2009 Asian Indoor Games|2009 Ho Chi Minh City]] | Team }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{nowrap|{{FlagIOC|AOI}}}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[Cue sports at the 2013 Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games|2013 Incheon]] | Singles }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[Cue sports at the 2013 Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games|2013 Incheon]] | Team }}\n}}\n\n'''Aditya Mehta''' (born 31 October 1985 in [[Mumbai, Maharashtra|Mumbai]], India) is an Indian former professional [[snooker]] player. He participated on the [[World Snooker Tour]] for the 2007\u201308 season, and between 2011 and 2018. He reached a highest [[World snooker rankings|world ranking]] of 49. Mehta participated in the final of ranking event for the first time at the [[2013 Indian Open]] where he played [[Ding Junhui]], but lost 0\u20135.\n\nHe has several medals at the [[Asian Indoor Games|Asian]] and [[World Games]]. He won the gold at the men's event at the [[Cue sports at the 2013 World Games|2013 World Games]], and the team event at the [[Cue sports at the 2009 Asian Indoor Games|2009 Asian Games]]. Mehta compiled a total of 41 [[century break]]s whilst on tour, the highest of which was at the [[European Tour 2014/2015 \u2013 Event 2|2014 Paul Hunter Classic]] where he made his first ever [[maximum break]] in competition.\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nMehta was born on 31 October 1985 in [[Mumbai, Maharashtra]].<ref name=\"cues_Adit\" /> He began his career by playing [[Challenge Tour (snooker)|Challenge Tour]] from 2004.<ref name=\"Vowkn\" /> He was nominated for a Main Tour place for the [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/2009 season]] by the Asian Confederation of Billiard Sports after he finished as runner-up at the [[ACBS Asian Snooker Championship|2008 ACBS Asian Snooker Championship]].<ref name=\"SRGdm\" /><ref name=\"2008/2009 players\">{{cite web|title=2008\u20139 Main Tour Players|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/2008-9-Main-Tour-List.htm|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|accessdate=10 July 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219151526/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/2008-9-Main-Tour-List.htm|archivedate=19 December 2008}}</ref> He was the first Indian to play on the Main Tour since [[Yasin Merchant]] did in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Bangkok tuned me up for pro circuit: Mehta\" /> He was unable to retain his place on the Tour at the end of the season having not qualified for a single event but regained a place for the [[2011-12 Snooker season|2011\u20132012 season]] after being awarded the Asian nominated place.<ref name=\"2011/12 Tour Players\">{{Cite web |title=2011/12 Tour Players |date=17 May 2011 |work=World Snooker |publisher=World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2361634,00.html |accessdate=17 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521002818/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~2361634%2C00.html |archivedate=21 May 2011}}</ref> Aditya won both a bronze and silver medal in [[Cue sports at the 2010 Asian Games \u2013 Men's snooker singles|singles]] and [[Cue sports at the 2010 Asian Games \u2013 Men's snooker team|team]] events at the [[2010 Asian Games]] held in Guangzhou, China.<ref name=\"kk98z\" /><ref name=\"foTQz\" />\n\n===2011\u20132012 season: Asian champion===\nIn the 2011\u20132012 season, as a new player on tour, Mehta would need to win four qualifying matches to reach the main stages of all ranking events. At the second event of the season, the [[2011 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], Mehta defeated [[Stuart Carrington]] 5\u20130, [[Rod Lawler]] and [[Jamie Jones (snooker player)|Jamie Jones]] both 5\u20134, before losing to former world number six [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] 2\u20135.<ref name=\"kQVgJ\" /> He played in 10 of the 12 [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012|Players Tour Championship events]] this season, with his best result coming in [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 9|ninth event]] where he beat two-time [[World Snooker Championship]] runner-up [[Matthew Stevens]] 4\u20133 in the last 16, but then lost to [[Martin Gould]] 1\u20134 in the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"vzg80\" /> In April, Mehta won the [[2012 Asian Snooker Championship]] with a 7\u20135 victory over compatriot [[Pankaj Advani (billiards player)|Pankaj Advani]].<ref name=\"imLYq\" /> He finished the snooker season ranked world number 80 and therefore out of the top 64 who retain their places for the next season. However, as he won the Asian championship he earned a spot on the tour for the [[Snooker season 2012/2013|following season]].<ref name=\"ranking\" />\n\n===2012\u20132013 season: First ranking appearance===\nMehta started the 2012\u201313 season at the [[2012 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]]. He beat Sam Baird 5\u20133, [[James Wattana]] and [[Jimmy White]] both 5\u20131, but then lost out to [[Jamie Cope]] 4\u20135 in the final qualifying round.<ref name=\"2012/13\">{{cite web |url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=108&season=2012 |title=Aditya Mehta 2012/2013 |publisher=Snooker.org |accessdate=8 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711014747/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=108&season=2012 |archive-date=11 July 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> He also lost in the final qualifying round for the [[2012 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] following a 3\u20135 defeat to [[Mark King (snooker player)|Mark King]].<ref name=\"2012/13\" />\n\nMehta reached the main stage of a ranking event for the first time in his career in August, by qualifying for the [[2012 International Championship|International Championship]]. He overcame Michael Leslie and [[Mike Dunn (snooker player)|Mike Dunn]], both 6\u20133 and then came back from 3\u20135 behind to beat Jimmy White 6\u20135.<ref name=\"2012/13\" /><ref name=\"howjn\" /> In the last qualifying round he defeated Jamie Cope 6\u20134 to seal his place at the event in [[Chengdu]], China.<ref name=\"2012/13\" /> At the event he defeated [[Zhu Yinghui]] in the [[wild card (sports)|wildcard]] round, before winning 6\u20134 against [[Stuart Bingham]] to reach the last 16 where he played world number two [[Judd Trump]].<ref name=\"2012/13\" /><ref name=\"Indian Express Runs Down Bingham\" /> In his first televised match in a ranking tournament Mehta was [[whitewash (sport)|whitewash]]ed 0\u20136 by Trump.<ref name=\"Indian Express Runs Down Bingham\" /> However, his run in the tournament matched the best performance by an Indian player in a ranking event set by Yasin Merchant over two decades earlier.<ref name=\"hUhYH\" /> Mehta did not qualify for another event this season with his year ending in the second round of [[2013 World Snooker Championship#Qualifying|World Championship qualifying]], following a 9\u201310 loss to [[Alan McManus]].<ref name=\"f35SC\" /> He finished the season ranked world number 73.<ref name=\"qO9FB\" />\n\n[[File:Aditya Mehta at Snooker German Masters (Martin Rulsch) 2014-01-29 01.jpg|thumb|Mehta at the [[2014 German Masters]]]]\n\n===2013\u20132014 season: Ranking event finalist===\nIn July 2013, Mehta won the singles event at the [[Snooker at the World Games 2013 \u2013 men's singles|World Games]] by beating [[Liang Wenbo]] 3\u20130.<ref name=\"4AbP7\" /> The [[Snooker season 2013/2014|2013/2014 season]] saw the introduction of the [[2013 Indian Open|Indian Open]], the first ranking event held in India. Mehta reached the event for it by defeating [[Xiao Guodong]] 4\u20132 in qualifying.<ref name=\"2013/14\">{{cite web |url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=108&season=2013 |title=Aditya Mehta 2013/2014 |publisher=Snooker.org |accessdate=16 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609015611/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=108&season=2013 |archive-date=9 June 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the first round of the event held he made a break of 127 in the deciding frame against [[Peter Ebdon]] to win 4\u20133 and then beat Hammad Miah 4\u20131 to reach the last 16 for the second time in his career.<ref name=\"jThWS\" /><ref name=\"aTX6D\" /> Mehta defeated two-time world champion [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] 4\u20132 to face compatriot Pankaj Advani.<ref name=\"iIUpy\" /> Mehta defeated Advani to reach the semi-finals.<ref name=\"FqWEy\" /> He then me [[Stephen Maguire]] who he defeated on a {{cuegloss|deciding frame}} 4\u20133 to reach the final.<ref name=\"6ZohA\" /> In his first ranking event final, Mehta played [[Ding Junhui]], but was unable to win a frame, losing 0\u20135. As the tournament runner-up, Mehta won \u00a325,000.<ref name=\"liogM\" /> A month later he was beaten in the quarter-finals of the minor-ranking [[European Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 7|Antwerp Open]] 4\u20130 by [[Jack Lisowski]] and finished 29th on the [[Players Tour Championship 2013/2014#European Tour|Order of Merit]], just outside the top 25 who reached the [[Players Tour Championship 2013/2014 \u2013 Finals|PTC finals]].<ref name=\"mfrFJ\" /> Mehta's was unable to advance beyond the first round of a ranking event for the remainder of the season.<ref name=\"2013/14\" /> He increased his ranking by 24 places during the season to end it as the world number 49, retaining his place on Tour.<ref name=\"BT2Oa\" />\n\n===2014\u20132015 season: Maximum break===\nMehta did not come through the qualifying rounds of the first three ranking events of the [[2014-15 snooker season 2014/2015|2014\u20132015 season]], before beating James Wattana 6\u20133 to play in the [[2014 International Championship|International Championship]] where he was whitewashed 6\u20130 by [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]] in the first round.<ref name=\"2014/15\">{{cite web |title=Aditya Mehta 2014/2015 |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2014&player=108 |publisher=Snooker.org |accessdate=27 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706113341/http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=108&season=2014 |archive-date=6 July 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Mehta made his first [[maximum break]] in his second round loss against Stephen Maguire at the [[2014 Paul Hunter Classic]] PTC event.<ref name=\"147max\" />\n\nAt the [[2014 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] he defeated [[Alex Davies (snooker player)|Alex Davies]] 6\u20134, before losing 6\u20131 to Judd Trump in the second round.<ref name=\"64Rtb\" /> He reached the last 32 of a ranking event for the first time this year by defeating Sydney Wilson 4\u20130 and world number five [[Barry Hawkins]] 4\u20132 at the [[2015 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], but Alan McManus beat Mehta 0\u20134.<ref name=\"Gd89c\" /> At the [[2015 Indian Open]], Mehta held a 3\u20130 lead over Mark King and missed a shot on match-ball to win 4\u20131. Instead, King levelled at 3\u20133 and Mehta took the deciding frame to play world number eight [[Ricky Walden]] in the second round.<ref name=\"X031z\" /> Mehta was defeated 4\u20132 and stated that the difference between the 50 world ranking positions was \"obvious in the match\".<ref name=\"KuElz\" /> His only match before the end of the season was a 10\u20137 loss to [[Jak Jones]] in the opening round of [[2015 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] qualifying.<ref name=\"2014/15\" />\n\n===2015\u20132016 season: Neck injury===\nMehta qualified for the [[2015 International Championship]], but lost in the wildcard round 6\u20134 to local amateur player Wang Yuchen.<ref name=\"2015/16\">{{cite web |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=108&season=2015 |title=Aditya Mehta 2015/2016 |publisher=Snooker.org |accessdate=2 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725175014/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=108&season=2015 |archive-date=25 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Before the [[2015 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] he stated that a neck injury sustained in 2014 had been affecting his practice hours and confidence in his game.<ref name=\"2erUT\" /><ref name=\"Resigns\" /> Mehta defeated Sam Baird 6\u20135 at the UK Championship, before losing 6\u20132 to [[Neil Robertson]] in the second round.<ref name=\"2015/16\" /> In February 2016, in order to recover from his neck injury he pulled out of the remaining events for the season.<ref name=\"Resigns\" /> At the end of the season, he gained a two-year pass to retain his place on tour after finishing 53rd on the [[Players Tour Championship 2015/2016#European Tour|European Order of Merit]].<ref name=\"dgGNs\" />\n\n===2016\u20132017 season===\nMehta qualified again for the [[2016 International Championship]] by beating Jack Lisowski 6\u20134 and then eliminated Ryan Day 6\u20132. At the event he lost 6\u20133 to [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]].<ref name=\"snoo_Inte\" /> He was defeated 4\u20133 after having been 3\u20130 ahead of [[Anthony McGill]] in the second round of the [[2016 Northern Ireland Open|Northern Ireland Open]].<ref name=\"cbiQP\" /> He also got to the second round of the [[2016 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] before losing 4\u20132 to [[Noppon Saengkham]].<ref name=\"snoo_Cora\" /> Mehta won 5\u20132 over Barry Hawkins in qualifying for the [[2017 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] and he won three frames to tie his first round match with [[Li Hang (snooker player)|Li Hang]] at 4\u20134, but lost the deciding frame.<ref name=\"rO4dJ\" /><ref name=\"q3r21\" /> Mehta finished the season ranked 80th in the world.<ref name=\"World Rankings \u2013 World Snooker\" />\n\n===2017\u201318 season: Return to amateur status===\nAt the [[2017 China Championship (snooker)|2017 China Championship]], Mehta lost in the opening round to [[Ali Carter]] 5\u20134.<ref name=\"snoo_Ever\" /> At the third ranking event of the season, the [[2017 Riga Masters|Riga Masters]], Mehta defeated [[Rory McLeod (snooker player)|Rory McLeod]] 4\u20132, before losing to Jamie Cope by the same scoreline in the second round.<ref name=\"snoo_Kasp\" /> The [[2017 English Open (snooker)|English Open]] was Mehta's best performance since the 2015 Indian Open. Mehta defeated Sam Craigie 4\u20130, [[Ian Preece]] 4\u20132 and [[Chen Zifan]] 4\u20131 to reach the last 16 of a ranking event for the third time.<ref name=\"euro_LIVE\" /> Mehta played Neil Robertson, who he lost 4\u20131 to.<ref name=\"euro_LIVE\" /><ref name=\"snoo_Dafa\" />\n\nAt the [[2017 UK Championship]], Mehta defeated Sam Baird in the opening round on a deciding frame 6\u20135, but lost in the second round to [[Luca Brecel]] 6\u20133.<ref name=\"snoo_Betw\" /> Mehta reached the second round of the [[2018 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] defeating [[Martin O'Donnell]], before losing to [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]].<ref name=\"snoo_ManB\" /> Mehta's final ranking appearance of the season was at the [[2018 Gibraltar Open|Gibraltar Open]], where he reached the third round. He defeated Brian Ochoiski and [[Kurt Dunham]] before losing to [[Tian Pengfei]].<ref name=\"Y0WUS\" /> His final match of the season was in the first round of qualifying for the [[2018 World Snooker Championship]], where he lost 8\u201310 to [[Zhao Xintong]].<ref name=\"wtb3I\" /><ref name=\"Qualiresults\" /> Mehta finished the season outside of the top-64 in the [[Snooker world rankings 2017/2018|world rankings]], and did not retain his place on the World Snooker Tour.<ref name=\"World Rankings \u2013 World Snooker\" /><ref name=\"worl_Main\" /> After returning to being an amateur player, Mehta played less due to his neck issues. However, in 2019 alongside [[Pankaj Advani-Aditya]] the pair won the [[IBSF World Team Snooker Championship]], defeating the Thai team 3\u20131.<ref name=\"indi_Pank\" /><ref name=\"hind_Pank\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is a brand ambassador of snooker website ''rkgsnooker.com'' where he writes regular blog posts and columns.<ref name=\"Qacwt\" /> He practises with [[Alfie Burden]] and [[Anthony Hamilton (snooker player)|Anthony Hamilton]] in London.<ref name=\"4wCuN\" /> He is sometimes referred to as the \"sun of Indian snooker\".<ref name=\"rkgs_AVer\" /><ref name=\"desi_5Top\" />\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\" scope=\"column\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[Snooker season 2004/2005|2004\u2013<br />05]]\n! [[Snooker season 2008/20